y -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExploring theater practices in communist and post-communist Hungary, Romania and Bulgaria, this book analyzes intertextuality or "inter-theatricality" as a political strategy, designed to criticize contemporary political conditions while at the same time trying to circumvent censorship. Plays by Romanian, Hungarian and Bulgarian dramatists are examined, who are "retrofitting" the past by adapting the political crimes and horrifying tactics of totalitarianism to the classical theatre (with Shakespeare a favorite) to reveal the region's traumatic history. By the sustained analysis of the aesthetic devices used as political tools, Orlich makes a very strong case for the continued relevance of the theater as one of the subtlest media in the public sphere. She embeds her close readings in a thorough historical analysis and displays a profound knowledge of the political role of theater history. In the Soviet bloc the theater of the absurd, experimentation, irony, and intertextual distancing (estrangement) are not seen as mere aesthetic language games but as political strategies that use indirection to say what cannot be said directly.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2022) 0aCommunism and literaturezEurope, Eastern. 0aEast European dramay20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEast European drama--20th century--History and criticism. 0aEnglish dramaxAdaptationsxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench dramaxAdaptationsxHistory and criticism. 0aRussian dramaxAdaptationsxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aCensorship, Communism, Cultural studies, Drama, Freedom of expression, Postcommunism, Theater.1 aKomporaly, Josefina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo